Stats of NBA Players by Hyun Jin Lee

Abstract

NBA is one of the premier sports organization, with lots of young aspiring athletes trying to make it to the “Biggest Stage of All”. So, what traits make a great athelete? Basketball once was deemed a sport of bigs, such as Shaq, who dominated the paint zone. Now, the era is defined by a term, “small ball” - smaller and agile guards, with skills. What makes an athlete a great scorer? We are here to find out.

Dataset

The dataset is from Kaggle, with the work done by DrGuillermo scraping Basketball-reference[https://www.basketball-reference.com]. His data includes all players from 1950 to 2016, but as we are only looking at the modern NBA atheletes, and 2017 season is incomplete in this dataset, our analysis will revolve around the 2016-17 season. It includes all players that were on the roster during 2016-17 season and played more than a minute throughout the season.

There are only two players, out of 578, who have a dual-position as their position. For the consistency, these outliers were addressed manually. As Frye is registered as forward on official NBA website, his position was adjusted as such. However, Sonny Weems is a different case - he was, indeed, a tweener, and was assigned both SG and SF for his role. Since he is an extreme outlier, and the sample size is big enough that the exemption of one sample will not change the statistics dramatically, I’ve decided exclude Sonny Weems sample from the dataset.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0   105.0   338.0   466.3   700.0  2376.0

Transformed the long-tail data using log10, to better understand the distribution of total points between players. There seems to be a unimodal peak near 1000 region. Generally, more minutes played, more chance for points an athelete gets. So, how about the minutes played?

Both total points and minutes played show a similar pyramidic pattern, with only a handful making their way up top. Then, I wonder, would points per minute played be drastically different from those patterns?

Quite surprisingly, points per minute actually shows a unimodal, normal-like curve with the mean around 0.39, with a few glaring outliers.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

Now that we examined PTS & minutes played, turning it into point per minute, I want to examine other indicators that conjure up the offense. For field goals, I believe that the FG% is a better indicator of a scorer’s ability than numbers made or attempted, so I will examine that as a main feature of field goal.

There are 578 players in the dataset with 56 features. Position is a factor variable with the following level.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features in the data set are points per minute and field goal percentage, which is divisible into two-pointer % and three-pointer %. I want to determine which features are the best for predicting the points per minute for a player. I suspect that the field goal percentage, along with some other variables, will affect the points per minute, thereby help build a predictive model for the points scored.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I believe that the performance features that I’ve explored above, such as steals, and offensive rebounds, will support my investigation into points per minute and field goal percentage.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Points per minute(PPM) variable was derived from (total points scored / minutes played). This is a better indicator of the athlete’s proficiency in scoring than total points scored, which can be biased by the length of their playing time. Also, assist / steal / offensive rebounds / turnover are all converted to a per minute metric.

Before we dive into the variables, let’s make sense of the correlation of our main variable, points per minute(PPM), to other possibly affecting variables.

Pearson’s correlation of variables against PPM shows that there two indicators showing modest correlation - field goal percentage (FG.) and turnovers per minute(TPM).

There are three interesting things to note: 1. Field goal percentage as a whole has much higher correlation, when compared to the broken down components of field goal percentage : 2-pointer percentage and 3-pointer percentage.

  1. Turnover has a relatively high correlation with points per minute, which is quite surprising - generally, one would think that having more turnovers would undermine one’s ability to score.

  2. Physical profile such as height & weight, is seemingly unrelated with the athletes’ point scoring ability.

Let’s examine the first point, with field goal percentage, 2-pointer percentage, and 3-pointer percentage in relation to point per minute.

To take a closer look at the main area, let’s zoom in:

Field Goal Percentage is defined by (X2P + X3P) / (X2PA + X3PA), thus is related directly to 2-pointer percentage, defined by (X2P / X2PA), and 3-pointer percentage, defined by (X3P / X3PA). Thus, when linear modelling, including field goal percentage along with 2-pointer percentage and 3-pointer percentage will likely cause a colinearity issue. Since Field Goal Percentage has higher correlation with point per minute, it might as well be one of our choice of the variables in linear model.

Now, we can address our second point in question - that is, the question of high correlation between turnover per minute(TPM) and point per minute. It is quite counter-intuitive, as turnover generally means that you coughed up your ball, and in general, ball handling is emphasized in the pro scene.

A positive tendency is quite strong. Let us examine the concentrated area, from around 0.01 to 0.1.

The tendency seems even clearer, even though there seems to be a spread towards the higher end, a bit like a cone shape. Let’s examine some of the high TOM personnels, in top 90% percentile.

Furthermore, the correlation between turnover per minute and assist per minute is even higher than that between turnover per minute and points per minute. This is also quite reasonable, as our list of top turnover per minute athletes were the primary ball handlers for the team, leading attack and responsible for scoring and creating for teammates.

How about the positions? We know that positions define the role, with the centers and power forwards operating nearer to the goal. Guards, generally, operate on the perimeter. Does the position of an athlete have any impact?

This density plot shows an odd trend in field goal percentage and point per minute concerning centers. The centers, while having point per minute density similar to other positions, have higher field goal percentage compared to the other positions.

This difference is even more stark when looking at box plot for field goal percentage, segmented by positions. Centers have a very high inter-quartile range, with the median way above the other positions. This relationship between field goal percentage, point per minute, and position poses an interesting question, and thus will be examined further in the multivariate section.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

My main feature of interest, points per minute, had moderate positive correlation with field goal percentage (FG.) and turnovers per minute(TPM), both positive. Also, it had positive correlation with free throw percentage, as well.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features

Turnovers per minute(TPM) has a strong positive correlation with assist per minute(APM), which is quite plausible as the athletes whose turnovers per minute was the highest were the primary ball handlers for their team. Also, centers had higher field goal percentage relatively.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship that I found was that between field goal percentage and points per minute. Multivariate Plots Section

As you can see, for most of the positions, field goal percentage seems to have a positive linear correlation with points per minute. However, for center position, the field goal percentage does not show such a correlation. The correlation between points per minute and field goal percentage, for centers, is small as shown below:

## [1] -0.02924458

Excluding the centers, the correlation between points per minute and field goal percentage becomes quite strong:

## [1] 0.4929063

This is greater than the correlation as whole.

This, along with the plots of field goal percentage and positions done at the bivariate section, implies that centers generally have higher field goal percentage when compared to other positions. It is reasonable, as centers, generally, shoot a lot closer to the rim than most of the other positions.

When visualized, centers reside much closer to the lower-right cluster of field goal percentage - point per minute plot, with higher field goal percentage and lower point per minute. Also, higher spread compared to other positions, if not regarding the outliers.

The field goal percentage, as a whole, shows a weak linear relationship with the points per minute, meaning that it can be, indeed, a variable which can be used to predict the point per game. However, given the big spread, the statistical power of the model will be quite weak.

Reflection

This dataset contains information on all players and their stats from 1950 - 2017(partial). However, to better reflect modern basketball, I’ve only used 2016-2017 as my sample. I started by looking through individual variables, making estimates on which variable might be impactful on my main variable, which was point per minute.

The trend between field goal percentage and points per minute was found, albeit not very strong. I was surprised by the fact that the position actually had a big impact on field goal percentage. Centers were, in general, more efficient in scoring field goals then others. I hoped I have a bit more data to dive in and elaborate on this phenomenon. Average shooting distance, for example, would be a great feature to have and analyze - I’m quite sure this is what contributed to the scoring efficiency of the centers.

There are some limitations with this approach: This season may be an abnormality when compared to other seasons. Also, it is based on the game statistics, which can be bolstered by the addition of several features. Also, my model was quite off, primarily due to the data having great spread in terms of field goal percentage and points per minute.
